# ✅ Real React Currying Examples (With Explanations)

***

## ✅ 1️⃣ Event Handler with Dynamic Parameters (MOST COMMON 🔥)

### ✅ Problem

You want to pass an argument to an event handler **without calling it immediately**.

***

### ✅ Without Currying (Inline Arrow – Less Reusable)

```jsx
<button onClick={() => handleClick(id)}>Click</button>
```

Works, but creates a **new function on every render**.

***

### ✅ With Currying (Preferred Pattern)

```jsx
const handleClick = (id) => () => {
  console.log("Clicked ID:", id);
};

<button onClick={handleClick(id)}>Click</button>
```

### ✅ Why This Is Currying

```js
handleClick(id)    // returns a function
() => { ... }      // executed on click
```

✅ Cleaner  
✅ Reusable  
✅ Interview‑approved pattern

***

## ✅ 2️⃣ Form Handling (Field‑Specific Handlers)

### ✅ Problem

Multiple inputs but one handler.

***

### ✅ Using Currying

```jsx
const handleChange = (field) => (event) => {
  setFormData(prev => ({
    ...prev,
    event.target.value
  }));
};

<input onChange={handleChange("email")} />
<input onChange={handleChange("password")} />
```

### ✅ Why It’s Powerful

✅ One handler  
✅ No duplicate functions  
✅ Scales to many fields

📌 **Very popular in forms**

***

## ✅ 3️⃣ Toggle / Action by ID (Lists)

### ✅ Example: Todo List

```jsx
const toggleTodo = (id) => () => {
  setTodos(todos =>
    todos.map(todo =>
      todo.id === id ? { ...todo, done: !todo.done } : todo
    )
  );
};

{todos.map(todo => (
  <button key={todo.id} onClick={toggleTodo(todo.id)}>
    Toggle
  </button>
))}
```

✅ Captures `id`  
✅ Executes later  
✅ Closure + currying working together

***

## ✅ 4️⃣ Curried Handler with `useCallback` (Performance‑Safe)

```jsx
const handleDelete = useCallback(
  (id) => () => {
    setItems(items => items.filter(i => i.id !== id));
  },
  []
);

<button onClick={handleDelete(item.id)}>Delete</button>
```

✅ Avoids unnecessary re‑creations  
✅ Works well with `React.memo`

***

## ✅ 5️⃣ API Call Builder (Very Practical ✅)

```js
const apiCall = (method) => (url) => async (body) => {
  const res = await fetch(url, {
    method,
    body: JSON.stringify(body),
  });
  return res.json();
};

const postUser = apiCall("POST")("/users");

// usage
postUser({ name: "Raja" });
```

✅ Clean API abstraction  
✅ Highly reusable  
✅ Interview‑friendly

***

## ✅ 6️⃣ Permission‑Based Rendering

```jsx
const hasPermission = (role) => (user) =>
  user.roles.includes(role);

const isAdmin = hasPermission("admin");

{isAdmin(user) && <AdminPanel />}
```

✅ Functional  
✅ Declarative  
✅ Clean logic separation

